Iskra Lawrence wants people to know that anyone can struggle with an eating disorder: "We think of 'eating disorder' and immediately go to a white anorexic woman," Lawrence says. "But that's not the case. Eating disorders have many different forms." 
.
FULL STORY: https://bit.ly/3xCNVo9

After experiencing severe bloating, Dafina Malovska went to see her doctor who brushed it off and told her it was food-related. "My stomach was so swollen I couldn't even see my feet when I looked down," she said. Knowing something wasn't right, she decided to get a second opinion. That's when they discovered it—a 5.5-inch tumor on her uterus. 
.

"So many people believe having babies ruins your body," said #EmilySkye on a recent post. She wants to remind you that that's not true: "Your body is not ruined, it’s just different! ⁣Just because your body has changed & may never be the same, doesn’t mean it isn’t fit, strong or beautiful.⁣⁣⁣⁣"
.
She went on to give advice for anyone who may be struggling with this. "Focus on what your body does for you every single day rather than how it looks or what you can’t change. ⁣⁣⁣⁣Every body is amazing & beautiful & should be celebrated. Easier said than done I know, but if we don’t start practicing it things will never change.⁣⁣"
.
Skye then talked about how she hopes her 3-year-old daughter, Mia, will be body-positive. "I want my daughter Mia to love her body no matter what and not compare herself to other people or strive for this idea of perfection like I used to," she said. "The best way to help our kids I believe is to lead by example. Let them see us being kind to ourselves and loving ourselves and our bodies.🤍 It all starts with us.⁣⁣⁣⁣"
.
Tap the link in bio for the full story 👆

node.text:
Sarah of @shesinscrubs recently shared what it's like to work as a RN right now: "We are so tired. Our hospital admins are silently expecting us to push forward in rapidly deteriorating conditions,” she explained. “Instead of retaining core staff the last 18 months they pushed us away. Our Covid census has now surpassed the peak in 2020 with a skeleton of the workforce we had.”
.
She went on to paint a vivid picture of how rising COVID rates are causing overcrowding in hospitals: “Previously preserved ratios on PCU/ICU/MED-SURG Floors are no longer. With no protections for these nurses in states like Florida, ICU nurses will be tripled or even take 4 unstable patients. On PCU/Stepdown nurses are now taking 6-7 patients instead of 3-4.”
.
This doesn’t just impact COVID patients, she added. “AND THIS IS CRUCIAL TO NOTE. When there are no STAFFED beds on the inpatient floors, patients will be waiting in the ER. In hallways, in waiting areas, in makeshift areas. Some patients who are admitted can wait over 3 days on a stretcher to go to a bed. Patients who come in for things other than Covid risk exposure in the crowded ER hallways. ER nurses & techs must manage chaos in an over crowded environment. This is not safe for patients. This is not safe for staff.
.
People who say I complain too much, that I 'signed up for this,' don’t realize this is not just about ME.

This is about every single healthcare worker that can relate to each post. Because this is not just where I work.

This is a national crisis.

This is hurting patients."

node.text: Not all types of acne are the same; fungal acne, in particular, has an entirely different cause than most other types, which means—you guessed it—the treatment is different, too. Tap the link in bio to find out more about fungal acne, including who's at risk for it, how to identify it, and what you can do to treat it 👆

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Health on August 14, 2021. May be an illustration of 1 person and text that says 'How to Know if Your Acne Is Actually Caused by a Fungal Infection Health'.

Photo by Health on August 14, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'What is fungal acne? Most typical forms of acne are caused by clogged pores. But fungal acne has an entirely different source: a yeast called Malassezia. Malassezia yeast is a normal inhabitant of our skin, but it can overgrow in certain conditions. When it does, it causes inflammation of those same hair follicles and can result in acne. Health'.

Photo by Health on August 14, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'What causes fungal acne? The common causes are situations and environments that promote rapid yeast growth. Those can include: Living in hot, humid climates Having a high oil gland production Frequent sweating, either because of climate, exercise, or medical conditions Not changing into clean clothes after exercise •Certain medications, like antibiotics Wearing tight, restrictive clothing (especially in warmer temperatures) Some immunosuppressive conditions or medications Health'.

Photo by Health on August 14, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'What are the symptoms of fungal acne? Fungal acne is more common on the chest and back because of how those areas are often covered by our clothing (and thus more prone to becoming hot, sticky, sweaty, and poorly ventilated). Fungal acne may or may not look like typical acne; it's often itchy, with a rashy, uniform appearance. The red bumps also tend to appear at the same time. Health'.

Photo by Health on August 14, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'What are the treatment options for fungal acne? You have to target the overgrowth of yeast on your skin if you want to reduce your fungal acne. If your acne is mild, you can start by using an over-the-counter antifungal cream to control the balance of yeast on your skin. Most commonly, you will need an oral medication, as the yeast can be too deep in the follicles for the topical medications to get to. Dermatologists will often recommend a medicated wash as maintenance if someone becomes prone to this condition. Health'.

Photo by Health on August 14, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Can you prevent fungal acne? Since everyone has Malassezia yeast on their skin, you can't get rid of it completely. Instead, your goal is to find a routine that helps you keep the yeast in check: Avoid wearing tight or restrictive clothing for long periods of time. Shower and change into clean clothes after a workout or any activity that causes sweating. Use antifungal shampoo a few times per week as a body wash to prevent or limit breakouts. Consider using acne-fighting or exfoliating body washes. Health'.

Keva Drawns of @kevadenee shares her postpartum journey online and now she's opening up about getting this comment from other moms: "Your stomach may not look like mine because:
-you birthed 1 child.
-you have a longer torso.
-the beautiful baby your birthed may not have been on the bigger side.
-you have a stronger abdominal wall.
-you carried differently than I.
- our age differences.
- Our pelvic size/shape.”
.
Drawns hopes to bring awareness to Diastase Recti “and the reality of how some women look after giving birth” using her platform. She says she feels blessed to have “a forever mom body.”
.
“If you are a mama that snapped right back, that’s fine.
If you are a mama that has DR, that’s fine.
If you are a mama that is neither, that’s fine.

STOP COMPARING! Your body just wants to be appreciated for all the WERK it has been through."
